On my last trip to Kenya, I picked up these two pieces of art painted onto canvas of a mama and baby elephant and giraffe. At the time I was single, planning to become a foster mom someday, never imagining I would have a child of my own. I thought, “Maybe if I foster a baby one day, I can put these up in the room.”

Years go by, then I meet my husband. And we find out we are expecting and we start talking about the nursery. The memory hits me as I pull out these rolled up paintings untouched since I came back. It was overwhelming to see these going up in our son’s room today. He is the fulfillment of a dream I dared not allow myself to have for so many years. I didn’t think I’d ever be holding my own baby in a nursery in my own home but I am so excited to meet him this month.

Having some postpartum complications so I’m back in the hospital and prayers are appreciated, but laying here all I can think about is the moms who don’t have support systems. The moms who recover from birth or C-section alone, who wake up to feed their baby and don’t get a “break,” who end up sick or have a sick baby and don’t have others to lean on. I also think about how maternal healthcare in the US has gotten us where we are in foster care. The exhaustion that makes you make mistakes, the lack of maternity leave that means you go back to work bleeding and sore unable to spend that time bonding with your baby, the cost of daycare that leaves working parents with few options, and we wonder why parents struggle. Why people make mistakes and lose their kids when we’ve set them up to fail. When we judge parents and threaten them losing their kids instead of reaching out to the parents in our community and saying, “This shit is hard. I don’t want you to do it alone.” Because damn, it’s hard being sick and wanting to just care for your baby and not being able to. Thankfully, I have a full village who are taking shifts taking care of me AND baby. And to those of you who are struggling on this journey alone, I can’t tell you how proud I am of you. I hope you know that you are the only mama/daddy/parent that baby knows and they think you are doing amazing. That this parenting shit is hard and it’s ok to make mistakes. You are doing your best and some days, that isn’t a lot but it is ENOUGH. You are enough.

Update: We are ok. Grateful for the prayers and thoughts, I have felt your support in all of this. Celebrating the small wins like finally feeling up to holding baby by myself (he’s been with me the whole time but I haven’t been able to hold him on my own due to the treatment.) I also appreciate those who shared the importance of a village for new parents, how important giving grace and care to those doing this on their own, and for the ones who shared their own experiences. We as a country, as a community, as neighbors and as family, owe our votes to candidates who talk about issues that impact families like healthcare and parental leave, owe our support and grace to the parents we see who struggle and make mistakes, and owe our voices to speaking up to change things so children have healthy (physically and mentally) parents.

One of the lesser talked about parts of foster care is the community you build for life, even from the first classes. In my  licensing classes (1 when single, 1 when married) I met some incredible fellow foster parents who have become friends. We texted our nerves when we got our first placement, shared in our struggles, celebrated the wins, had cookouts and met each others kids, and provided respite for each other. They become a huge part of your village. And then when I had my baby, one couple met us for lunch and gave me a whole bag of baby boy clothes and bottles, another brought me dinner and this delicious homemade pound cake. So if you go through licensing classes, don't miss out on the relationships. Spend time bonding with your classmates and be a support system for each other. And then do life together.

A conversation today has sat heavy on me. Do you ever sit and think how many things you didn't have to experience because you were born to certain people? That someone across town from you was born on the same day to different people and suffered so much because they came from a different womb. I recognize how privileged my son is to have two parents who love him, who understand trauma and the impact of the time you spend with them and the words you say. If you had those things, be grateful. If your children do, be grateful. But for those who didn't because they were born to people who weren't ready or weren't able to parent them, know that it's not fair and you deserved to be treasured by those who made you. And I hope that you build a life surrounded by friends and partners who see how deep your value is and who give you the love you always deserved.

PERSONAL STORY TIME: On our family's flight from DC to Atlanta this week, my son was standing on my lap watching all the people coming on the plane. He was bouncing and holding onto the seat in front of us. Then the lady who had that seat put her things down and I was afraid she would be annoyed at the active baby behind her.

She wasn't. She smiled and played peekaboo and talked to him for several minutes. He was enamored with her. Then the lady sitting across from us said, "He's so personable, he may go into politics!" I joked and said we call him Mayor because he loves people and so he may end up in politics! The lady in front of us who had been playing with my son laughed and said, "He would be a great politician. I'm in politics so I know!"

As the plane left the gate, I did some internet sleuthing and found out who "the politician" in front of us was - US House Representative Lucy McBath of Georgia. And as I read her bio, I learned what an incredible woman she is.

Rep. McBath wasn't always a politician. She got involved in politics after her son, Jordan Davis (who she named after the River Jordan), was murdered. You may remember his case if you don't remember his name. A 45-year old white man shot up the vehicle that 17-year old Jordan was riding in when the man got mad because he felt the boys had their music up too loud at a gas station. Jordan was sitting in the back seat of his friend's car when he was killed. His life taken by a racist man with a temper - and a gun.

So Rep. McBath got involved in the work to address gun violence, and it's taken her all the way to Congress. Meaning the only reason she was on the plane playing with my little boy... was because she no longer had hers.

Sitting in economy, no fancy designer bag, no name badge or name dropping to those next to her. On her way back home to Atlanta. Being kind to the rambunctious baby and tired parents sitting behind her. 

May we all be so well represented by someone with so much passion for everyone's little boys. 

(I regret that we didn't get a photo with her, but she seemed to be ok with anonymity and we didn't want to ruin that for her.)

Rep. Lucy McBath

Ok non foster-related mom question... I found out today that we are supposed to send food to school with my 9 month old beyond just bottles 🤦‍♀️ and that since he's moved into his new class this week, he's just been watching the other kids eat. 😩 I know, I know, I get the bad mom award. But we feed him real food for breakfast and dinner and are doing mainly baby-led weaning cause he hates purées and he doesn't have teeth so we are still careful. He likes the consistency of like mashed potatoes, hummus, yogurt, guacamole. Am I going to be the weirdest mom if I send him to daycare with guacamole and hummus?!? What else can I send for him to eat that isn't a huge choking hazard but not purées? By the way, I never have these issues with teens, they eat everything 😂

One of the hardest parts of this work is deciding when to be the person they can call and steps in to help... and when to let natural consequences take effect. Even if you understand the 'why' - trauma, lack of family, being in survival mode for years - how do you help when they are adults and continue to make bad decisions. You want to be the parent they need and didn't have, you want to step in and save the day. But you also know at some point you aren't helping, you're enabling. So that's what I'm going to struggle with today... and we'll see what wins out - my heart or my head.
